      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in the context of buying a house, is basically a temporary holding place for money and documents until the deal is officially closed. Think of it like a highly secure, neutral third party—a professional escrow agent—who holds the buyer's deposit and the seller's proceeds. It's crucial because it protects both parties, ensuring that the money doesn't get to the seller until the buyer has the keys, and the house doesn't get to the buyer until the funds are verified. In a way, it's the ultimate safety net for your transaction.",
